{
  "doc_id": "37513",
  "text": "The answer to the first question is important since an early diagnosis is crucial to improve prognosis [CITATION_1] . It has been postulated that isolation of an Aspergillus species from respiratory samples in critically ill patients (even when immunocompetent) should not be routinely discarded as colonisation [CITATION_2] , but in elderly patients (commonly having underlying diseases) isolation is usually interpreted as colonisation [CITATION_3] . Confirmation of infection obliges the demonstration of histopathological evidence that is not usually feasible in this type of patients [CITATION_4] . Early administration of antifungals may be life-saving, but overinterpretation of the potential clinical significance of Aspergillus isolation may drive to needless treatments, with their associated problems and costs [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . How does clinicians solve the dilemma?",
